{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17528404","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17528404"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:42:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:42:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14299"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14299"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.14,0.58,0.04,0.21,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6994"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106770"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6994"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14299"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89250"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3029"},{"type":"tags","id":"4557"},{"type":"tags","id":"4674"},{"type":"tags","id":"4951"},{"type":"tags","id":"4971"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4989"},{"type":"tags","id":"4990"},{"type":"tags","id":"11632"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"},{"type":"tags","id":"13149"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"16556"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22750"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25035"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39242"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45710"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"106770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/106770"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman from Queensland presents to the General Practice clinic requesting a medical certificate for work. During the consultation, she appears distracted and anxious. When asked about her wellbeing, she hesitantly discloses that her partner of eight years has been \u0027rough\u0027 with her during arguments. On further questioning, she reveals episodes of choking during intercourse and appears uncomfortable discussing this. She minimises two previous presentations to different Emergency Departments with \u0027accidental\u0027 injuries. She works as a family lawyer and says her partner, a police officer, would lose his job if anyone found out about their \u0027private life\u0027. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well-groomed but anxious with pulse rate 100/min, blood pressure 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are fading bruises around her neck and wrists which she attributes to \u0027bedroom activities\u0027.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen asked directly about safety, she says, \u0022I know what you\u0027re thinking, but it\u0027s complicated. I see domestic violence cases every day in my work - this isn\u0027t like that. Besides, it would ruin both our careers.\u0022 \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mandatory report to police due to strangulation risk","Develop a safety plan with the patient","Arrange urgent psychiatric assessment","Document injuries and provide domestic violence resources only","Schedule joint consultation with her partner present"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case presents a complex situation involving domestic violence with several challenging factors: the patient\u0027s professional knowledge of domestic violence services, her partner\u0027s position of authority, and the presence of high-risk features including strangulation. The most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Edevelop a safety plan with the patient\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach acknowledges both the immediate danger and the complex barriers to disclosure while providing practical safety strategies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOne should note that requirements surrounding mandatory reporting vary by jurisdiction - for example, Northern Territory law requires all adults to report serious domestic and family violence to police. In Queensland, health professionals have mandatory reporting requirements where there is a child at significant risk of physical or sexual harm; they do not have a legal requirement to report an adult a risk of harm against their wishes. Reporting requirements in other states and territories are also determined by the presence of a child at risk of harm. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMandatory reporting to police\u003C/strong\u003E without the patient\u0027s consent, even with the high-risk feature of strangulation, could escalate the danger and destroy therapeutic alliance. Given the partner\u0027s position as a police officer, this could put her at increased risk. However, the risk of strangulation should be clearly documented and discussed with the patient as part of safety planning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArranging urgent psychiatric assessment\u003C/strong\u003E pathologizes the patient\u0027s legitimate fears and circumstances. While mental health support may be beneficial later, it should not be the primary response to domestic violence disclosure. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDocumenting injuries and providing resources only\u003C/strong\u003E is insufficient given the high-risk features present. While documentation is important, active safety planning is essential given the presence of strangulation and the partner\u0027s position of authority.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EScheduling a joint consultation\u003C/strong\u003E is dangerous and inappropriate in cases of suspected domestic violence. Couples counselling is contraindicated when there is active abuse, as it can increase risk to the victim.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe safety plan should include specific strategies accounting for the partner\u0027s role as a police officer, such as identifying safe contacts outside the local police force. The patient\u0027s legal knowledge should be leveraged to help her understand her rights and options, while acknowledging the unique barriers she faces as a professional in the legal system. Documentation should be particularly thorough given the high-risk features and potential future legal implications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Safety planning is crucial for individuals experiencing domestic violence, even if they are not ready to leave the relationship.","Motivational interviewing techniques can be used to explore ambivalence about leaving an abusive relationship without pressuring the patient.","Providing information about support services and resources is important, even if the patient is not ready to use them immediately."],"references":["Lynch J, Stone L, Victoire A. Recognising and responding to domestic and family violence in general practice. Australian journal of general practice. 2022 Nov 1;51(11):863-9.","Mandatory reporting. 1800RESPECT. 2024. Available from: https://www.1800respect.org.au/resources-and-tools/reporting-and-protection/mandatory-reporting","Telehealth and domestic and family violence. Queensland Health. June 2022. Available from: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/system-governance/policies-standards/guidelines/telehealth-domestic-family-violence"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89250"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14299"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":